description.plain:
Fazerdaze’s “Lucky Girl” is sung in the perspective of the girl. She spends her time acting uninterested and unattached to her significant other, though she faces the reality that she is in fact falling for them (and that she’s a lucky girl).

The video was shot on a 16mm Bolex film camera by Sam Kristofski, and then edited by Amelia Murray (Fazerdaze) herself.

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=My4j3vgFxbE

annotations:
And the thought of you leaving
 Gets heavier every day
 And my mind is deceiving
 What is it that I’m believing?
The narrator is having inner-thoughts of her lover leaving her as she has more doubts on the relationship, even though these doubts have no right to exist.
Are the walls getting closer

Amelia tells us about recording the bittersweet daydream “Lucky Girl” in the dark and solitary space in which she was living at the time:

I wrote and recorded this track while I was living in a room that had no windows – except for a skylight which I eventually had to block out to stop my room from overheating. It was so dark in there and I slowly began to feel sad, like the walls were enclosing on me – that’s how I got the idea for the first lyric

annotations:
Let it go now, Jennifer
 We were so young, Jennifer
 Are you still waiting and wasting my time?

Instead of letting go of the past Jennifer is still stuck on it not wanting to grow up. And by doing so Amelia feels that she’s wasting her time. This is what causes the rift in the friendship. One of them can’t wait for the future and confronts her fears while the other stays behind which breaks the bond between them.

Cos I was waiting on the other side of the road
 You’re always looking for a way to make me slow down

Amelia faced her fears early on, growing up and facing the real world. She already had “crossed the road” but Jennifer did not. As she waited on her friend to join her in facing fears and growing up Jennifer continued to try and slow down her pace.
Are you still waiting and wasting my fears?

Our fears are there to protect us but at some point we have to use that fear and uncertainty for the future as motivation to make something of ourselves. At some point we must overcome and grow as a person. Amelia is asking her childhood friend why she’s still wasting that fear and waiting instead of growing up and taking action.

Let it slip through your hands
 Let it slip through like the sand
She is saying that Jennifer should let her worries go and try to let them just pass by.

annotations:
I didn’t mean it or did I mean it?
 I think I might have said it, but wasn’t meaning to say it

Amelia talks about how she sees Fazerdaze as something separate to herself.

Her confusion around whether or not she said or meant something, could be down to the disconnect between her true self and her artistic persona.

If in doubt, pray to God
 It’s a shame no one’s listening
Amelia is desperately praying to God, despite claiming that God does not exist, or at least isn’t listening to her.
Well, I’m just gonna break, I’m just gonna break

I feel like I’ve been someone who’s pretty strong and resilient and I persevere with things, and I push myself really hard, and to sing the lyric “I’m just gonna break”, it just felt so real when it came out of my mouth. It was me dismantling this idea that I have to keep going, and I have to be strong, and I have to make everything work.

– Fazerdaze, RNZ
Look around her, three years wasted now

Amelia took three years off from music after releasing Morningside. She is acknowledging that these were three useless years.

This contradicts the short film “The Thich of It”, uploaded to the Fazerdaze YouTube channel, where Amelia mentions that this time off was necessary in order to feel happy as herself, rather than as Fazerdaze or as a part of a relationship.

description.plain: “Misread” may have to do with someone who’s down on their self (“today your head is down, your mind somewhere else”) and the sort of dichotomy that exists between really liking someone for their accomplishments (“something you did yourself”) and self-awareness (“as if you’re someone else”) and not liking their simultaneous level of self-pity (“I hate the way you talk about yourself when you’re feeling down”). So in that sense, the narrator is confused about her own feelings toward the person (“misread”).
